mes © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Deighton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Yorkshire and Durham): habitational name from any of several places in Yorkshire named Deighton, from Old English <i>dīc</i> ‘ditch, dike’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘settlement, enclosure’. See also   Ditton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ditton","meanings":["English (Kent): habitational name from any of numerous places called Ditton, for example Ditton in Kent, Buckinghamshire, and Lancashire; Fen Ditton or Wood Ditton in Cambridgeshire; or Thames Ditton or Long Ditton in Surrey, all from Old English <i>dīc</i> ‘ditch, dike’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement, farmstead’."]},{"name":"Deaton","meanings":["English (Middlesex): variant of   Deighton  ."]},{"name":"Dinsdale","meanings":["English (northern): habitational name from Over Dinsdale (North Yorkshire) or Low Dinsdale (Durham), which stand on opposite sides of the Tees river. The name arises from Old English <i>Dīctūneshalh</i> ‘nook, recess (Old English <i>halh</i>) belonging to   Deighton  ’."]},{"name":"Deyton","meanings":["English: variant of   Deighton  ."]},{"name":"Dighton","meanings":["English (Huntingdonshire): variant of   Deighton  ."]},{"name":"Dayton","meanings":["English: variant of   Deighton  ."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":55,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William De Deighton was born in 1400, in Deighton, Yorkshire, England, his father, John de Deighton, was 23 and his mother, Isabel de Duffield, was 23. He married Joan de Morton in 1438, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 14 September 1456, in Yorkshire, England, at the age of 56."},"et":{"1400–14 September 1456":"1400–14. september 1456","1398–Male":"1398–Surnud","1400–1456":"1400–1456","1402–Male":"1402–Surnud","1402–1456":"1402–1456","–1537":"–1537","1438–1464":"1438–1464","1377–1404":"1377–1404","September 1456":"september 1456","1404":"1404","1402":"1402","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1455":"1455","1377":"1377","1464":"1464","1398":"1398","1397":"1397","14 September 1456":"14. september 1456"